This enables functions which have to work both when the
raw mode is already set and when it isn't:

```
fn query(some_args) -> Result<SomeType, SomeError> {
    use crossterm::terminal::*;
    let switch_to_raw = !is_raw_mode_enabled()?;
    if switch_to_raw {
        enable_raw_mode()?;
    }
    let res = query_in_raw(some_args);
    if switch_to_raw {
        disable_raw_mode()?;
    }
    res
}
```

The main change is changing the `Command` trait from:
```rust
trait Command {
    type AnsiType: Display;

    fn ansi_code(&self) -> Self::AnsiType;

    #[cfg(windows)]
    fn execute_winapi(&self, writer: impl FnMut() -> Result<()>) -> Result<()>;
    #[cfg(windows)]
    fn is_ansi_code_supported(&self) -> bool { ... }
}
```
to:
```rust
trait Command {
    fn write_ansi(&self, f: &mut impl fmt::Write) -> fmt::Result;

    #[cfg(windows)]
    fn execute_winapi(&self, writer: impl FnMut() -> Result<()>) -> Result<()>;
    #[cfg(windows)]
    fn is_ansi_code_supported(&self) -> bool { ... }
}
```

This avoids cloning in `Print`-like commands, and avoids allocating `String`s in other commands, as well as simplifying the `Command` trait.

I also had to rework command execution to do the actual logic in the `QueueableCommand` and `ExecutableCommand` traits since it's easier to write code in functions than macros. The macros are still there, they just call the functions in `command.rs`.
